1.visualizes the maximum temperatures by city over the specified time period.

The weather dataset  first fiter year 2012 to 2022 and then group by city wise.the generated data then visualizes these maximum temperatures by city over the specified time period.
weather_10yr <- weather %>%
  filter(year(time) >= 2012 & year(time) <= 2022)  # Update filtering condition

# Group by city and year, get max temp
temp_summary <- weather_10yr %>% 
  group_by(city, year = year(time)) %>%
  summarize(max_temp = max(tmax, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'city'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot max temp by city and year
ggplot(temp_summary, aes(x = year, y = max_temp, col = city)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(group = city)) +
  labs(title = "Max Temperature from 2012 to 2022",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Max Temp (C)") +
  scale_x_continuous(
    limits = c(2012, 2022),  # Set x-axis limits from 2012 to 2022
    breaks = seq(2012, 2022, by = 1)  # Set breaks at whole number intervals
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    limits = c(30, 50),  # Set y-axis limits from 35 to 40 degrees Celsius
    breaks = seq(30, 50, by = 1)  # Set breaks at intervals of 1 degree Celsius
  )

8.Analysis of Average AQI by Period of the Day

# Define a function to categorize the period of the day
categorize_period <- function(datetime) {
  hour <- hour(datetime)
  if (hour >= 4 && hour < 12) {
    return("Morning")
  } else if (hour >= 12 && hour < 17) {
    return("Afternoon")
  } else if (hour >= 17 && hour < 21) {
    return("Evening")
  } else {
    return("Night")
  }
}

# Add a new column for the period of the day
city_hour <- city_hour %>%
  mutate(PeriodOfDay = sapply(Datetime, categorize_period))

# Calculate the average AQI for each period of the day and City
avg_aqi_period <- city_hour %>%
  group_by(PeriodOfDay, City) %>%
  summarize(avg_AQI = mean(AQI, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'PeriodOfDay'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Create an  point graph by period of the day
 ggplot(avg_aqi_period, aes(x = City, y = avg_AQI, color = PeriodOfDay)) +
  geom_point(position = position_dodge(width = 0.5)) +
  labs(
    title = "Average AQI by Period of the Day",
    x = "City",
    y = "Average AQI",
    color = "Period of the Day"
  ) +theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90))

13.prediction of AQI based on air quality parameter using linear model

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
## 
## Attaching package: 'caret'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     lift
# Separate data into complete and incomplete (missing AQI) observations
complete_data <- station_day %>%
  filter(!is.na(AQI))

incomplete_data <- station_day %>%
  filter(is.na(AQI))

# Split complete data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123)
index <- createDataPartition(complete_data$AQI, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- complete_data[index, ]
test_data <- complete_data[-index, ]
test_data$Date <- as.Date(test_data$Date)

# Train model using specific features and generate predictions
lm_model <- lm(AQI ~ PM2.5 + PM10 + CO, data = train_data)
predictions <- predict(lm_model, newdata = test_data)

# Create results dataframe
results <- data.frame(Actual = test_data$AQI, Predicted = predictions,Year = as.numeric(format(test_data$Date, "%Y")))

# Plot Actual vs. Predicted AQI
ggplot(results, aes(Actual, Predicted)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Actual AQI", y = "Predicted AQI") +facet_wrap(~Year)+
  ggtitle('Actual vs. Predicted AQI')
## Warning: Removed 8472 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

OUTCOMES

On analyzing the different datasets,the following outcomes were able to achieve,

  1.The analysis indicates that Delhi recorded the highest temperature, reaching 48.1 degrees Celsius in 2017, followed by  Lucknow and Bhubaneswar.

  2.The analysis indicates that Lucknow recorded the highest percipitation, reaching 471mm in 1993, followed by Bhubaneswar.

  3.The analysis reveals that Rourkela city experienced its highest wind speeds during the autumn season.
  
  4.The analysis of the top air quality cities indicates Ahmedabad being among the highest in air pollution. Specifically,  in February 2018, the city recorded severe air quality for over 250 days, signifying a significant air quality issue. Furthermore, within that month, there were 25  days when the air quality was classified as severe, indicating a critical concern  for public health.
  
  5.The correlation analysis between AQI, temperature, and precipitation shows a relationship between air quality and weather variables. There might be correlations indicating how changes in temperature or precipitation levels can influence air quality measurements.
  
  6.An interactive map plotted with the information of top temperature and percipation city can be seen.

  7.Predicting AQI values based on the other related parameters.The linear modelling is used here to predict the  value of AQI based on the assumption that AQI values are dependent on the AQI parameters.

RESULTS AND DISCUSSIONS

  The analysis of meteorological data reveals several key findings regarding temperature,precipitation, wind speeds, and air quality across different cities in India.
  
  Delhi experienced the highest temperature of 48.1C in 2017 among the cities analyzed, indicating extreme heat events that can influence pollution levels and human health. Lucknow recorded the maximum precipitation of 471mm in 1993, followed by Bhubaneswar. High rainfall can potentially wash away particulate matter, improving air quality. However, it can also influence photochemical activity affecting ozone levels.
  
  Correlation analysis between air quality, temperature and precipitation suggested interrelationships between these variables. Meteorological factors like temperature, humidity,rainfall can influence pollutant concentrations through effects on emissions, chemical reactions and dispersion. Statistical modeling using techniques like linear regression demonstrated the ability to predict air quality from meteorological data to an extent.
  
  Delhi is leading in weather monitoring infrastructure having high number of activ stations.A  possible reason is there increased focus on bad air quality in delhi.
